1. Internal OpenShift Registry

OpenShift runs its own internal registry. To use images from it:

List image streams

oc get is


Pull an image using imageStreamTag

oc new-app <namespace>/<imageStreamName>:<tag>


Example:

oc new-app myproject/myapp:1.0


Ensure your service account has pull access
By default, the default service account in your project can pull images from its own namespace. For cross-namespace access, grant system:image-puller:

oc policy add-role-to-user system:image-puller system:serviceaccount:<target-namespace>:default -n <source-namespace>

2. External Registry (Docker Hub, Quay, Private Registry)
a) Public Images

For public images, just reference the image:

oc new-app docker.io/library/nginx:latest

b) Private Images

Create a secret with your registry credentials

oc create secret docker-registry myregistrykey \
  --docker-server=<registry-url> \
  --docker-username=<username> \
  --docker-password=<password> \
  --docker-email=<email>


Example:

oc create secret docker-registry myregcred \
  --docker-server=quay.io \
  --docker-username=jeyasingh \
  --docker-password=******** \
  --docker-email=jeyasingh@example.com


Link secret to your service account

oc secrets link default myregcred --for=pull


Use the image in a deployment or oc new-app

oc new-app quay.io/myuser/myimage:latest

3. Test Pulling Images

You can check if your pod can pull the image:

oc run testpod --image=<image> --restart=Never --rm -it


If authentication fails, the pod wonâ€™t start.

